## 8. Hub Write Discipline

The Hub API enforces rate limits on a 5-minute sliding window. A Hub write happens
on every state transition: job create, each chunk complete, job complete, job fail.
Do not add additional Hub writes beyond these four event types without explicit
approval, because doing so risks hitting the 429 rate limit.

The backoff implementation in `job_store._push_to_hub()` handles HTTP 429 with
exponential backoff starting at `BACKOFF_BASE_SECS` and capped at `BACKOFF_MAX_SECS`.
Do not catch HTTP 429 anywhere else in the codebase. Let it propagate to `_push_to_hub`.

The UI refresh in `app.py` must use `cache.get_system_status()` and must be triggered
by Gradio's `every=CACHE_POLL_INTERVAL_SECS` parameter on `demo.load()`. It must
never call `job_store.load_all_jobs()` or any Hub API for UI refresh purposes.

---

## 9. Audio Duration Is the Admission Signal — Not File Size

The admission controller routes jobs based on audio duration in seconds, not bytes.
File size is format-dependent (bitrate varies by codec) and is not a reliable proxy
for compute time. Duration must be obtained by calling
`inference/preprocess.get_audio_duration_secs(path)`, which uses `torchaudio.info()`
to read metadata without decoding the full file.

The admission check must happen before any audio is loaded into memory. If you are
writing a code path that loads audio before checking duration, you have the order wrong.

